Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
Intelligence Superabundance
Will AI steal our jobs, let us work less, or force us to do more, better?=
=C2=A0
Induced demand, Jevons Paradox, the Marchetti constant, and consumer psycho=
logy 101 suggest that the increased supply of intelligence will create more=
 demand for tasks that require intelligence, that we=E2=80=99ll turn gains =
in intelligence efficiency into ways of doing new things that weren=E2=80=
=99t previously feasible.=C2=A0
Instead of a zero sum competition with the bots, we might be on the cusp of=
 intelligence superabundance. We may the same amount of time working, we=E2=
=80=99ll just achieve much more in those hours than we currently do.=C2=A0
Parkinson=E2=80=99s Law =E2=80=93 that the amount of work expands to fill t=
he time available for its completion =E2=80=93 suggests that when each disc=
rete piece of work takes less time, the amount of work will expand to fill =
the rest of the time. But that=E2=80=99s just a rule of thumb.
We can examine it a little more rigorously with a little mental flip. Inste=
ad of thinking about AI as something separate from human intelligence, we s=
hould think of it as an increase in the overall supply of intelligence.=C2=
=A0
As internet pioneer David Gelernter wrote in a prescient 2010 piece, Dream =
Logic, The Internet, and Artificial Thought [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/9369c973-49d0-4216-b55a-9e2c0abcaf90?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9CHuman intelligence is the most va=
luable stuff in the cosmos, and we are always running short. A computer-cre=
ated increase in the world-wide intelligence supply would be welcome, to sa=
y the least.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0There=E2=80=99s latent demand for brainspace.
Treating intelligence as a resource with a growing supply, we can use econo=
mic theories like induced demand and Jevons Paradox, the Marchetti constant=
, and even observations from Jeff Bezos to explore the idea that with AI, h=
umans will need to do more, better.=C2=A0
Then the important question becomes not =E2=80=9CWill I lose my job?=E2=80=
=9D but =E2=80=9CWhat would I do with superabundant intelligence?=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99ll get there, but first, a little econ.=C2=A0
Induced Demand and Jevons Paradox
Induced demand is one of the funniest concepts in economics, and I think it=
=E2=80=99s one of the most important to understand in an environment of abu=
ndance, be it physical or digital.=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s a simple definition: induced demand occurs when an increase =
in the supply or capacity of a good, service, or resource leads to an incre=
ase in its consumption. Supply begets demand.=C2=A0
This isn=E2=80=99t true of everything, of course. 10x=E2=80=99ing soda prod=
uction wouldn=E2=80=99t increase soda consumption by 10x. Induced demand ma=
inly holds in cases where there=E2=80=99s latent demand, where people would=
 use more of a thing if only more existed, or existed accessibly enough to =
use.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Traffic is the canonical, super frustrating example. The idea is that addin=
g new roads or lanes does practically nothing to reduce traffic. More cars =
just hit the road to fill up the new capacity, and the traffic is right bac=
k where it started. The result is that more people are stuck in traffic.
Casey Handmer has a good blog post on this [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
4c20ed71-3f9f-40f1-9287-0100f49df1f7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. He explains that latent demand for road spa=
ce in LA is ~30x the current capacity, meaning that ~3% of people who would=
 want to travel actually drive. The other 97% find the experience of drivin=
g in LA too painful, so they just don=E2=80=99t do it. When a new lane open=
s up, some of the people right on the pain border get optimistic that maybe=
 things will be less painful now, so they jump in their car and on the road=
, and create more pain for themselves and others by doing so. This would be=
 the case until LA builds at least 30x the road capacity.=C2=A0
But say you could build enough road to serve all of the latent demand and t=
hen some, effectively eliminating traffic. This would be a miracle and take=
 far more money and space than it=E2=80=99s worth, but just go with me. In =
this world, say the time it takes you to travel from home to work is cut in=
 half. There=E2=80=99s another funny economics quirk that comes into play h=
ere, too.=C2=A0
Jevons Paradox, named after economist William Stanley Jevons who first noti=
ced it in his 1856 book The Coal Question, states that when something becom=
es more efficient, people consume more of it. Jevons observed that when the=
 steam engine became more efficient, when it could do more using less coal,=
 coal consumption actually increased. People didn=E2=80=99t just use steam =
engines to do the same things more cheaply; they started using the steam en=
gine to do more things.=C2=A0
We can project this forward, too. In my favorite piece on the subject, Ener=
gy Superabundance [ https://substack.com/redirect/1a05fd4a-87a7-4b03-a76d-b=
c519710a3b1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ], Eli Dourado and Austin Vernon imagine what humans will be able to do=
 with energy nearly too cheap to meter. Their goal =E2=80=9Cin promoting ab=
undant energy is faster economic growth and higher standards of living.=E2=
=80=9D Among other things, they paint a =E2=80=9Cvision of the future that =
includes flying cars, hyperloop, sub-orbital point-to-point travel, electri=
c autonomous trucking, vertical farming, water-from-air condensation, water=
 desalination, and so much more.=E2=80=9D We won=E2=80=99t only use cheap, =
abundant energy to do the same things more cheaply; we=E2=80=99ll use it to=
 do more things, better and faster.
Both Bertrand Russell and Yacov Zahavi observed a similar phenomenon in tra=
vel. Since Neolithic times, people have budgeted roughly one hour per day f=
or commuting =E2=80=93 this hour is known as Marchetti=E2=80=99s constant [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/5459e3fe-5da4-48d6-95e6-b2d30dc54883?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] or the =E2=80=
=9Ctravel time budget.=E2=80=9D As transportation options have improved, pe=
ople have just traveled farther. Instead of walking to the next village, we=
 drive from the suburb to the city.=C2=A0
Jevons Paradox =E2=80=93 that increasing efficiency leads to more demand =
=E2=80=93 is one mechanism by which induced demand can occur. I call it out=
 specifically because it highlights how counterintuitive this stuff can be.=
=C2=A0
Create cheap, abundant clean energy, and people will consume a lot more ene=
rgy to do all sorts of wonderful things [ https://substack.com/redirect/e72=
955ac-2c17-4c44-ab5a-d19179f7d9f2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. ChatGPT tells me that energy efficient applian=
ces may actually lead to more energy usage at the population level as consu=
mers use their energy-efficient appliances more often (although my ChatGPT =
editor advised me to mention that this is a debated topic and not a univers=
ally accepted fact).=C2=A0
Make healthcare more accessible, and people will consume more healthcare. C=
hatGPT tells me that Europeans visit the doctor more often than Americans, =
but in the interest of balance, counters that Americans have higher consump=
tion rates of surgeries. Extrapolating: make doctors more accessible, decre=
ase the need for surgeries, increase health.
Increase the supply of services for which latent demand exists, and people =
should consume those services more frequently.
The Verdict on Lawyers=C2=A0
A couple weeks ago in Idea Olympics [ https://substack.com/redirect/901ac95=
9-c7a2-44a5-ab22-2a6bdaef56fe?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], I imagined a future in which LawBots take human la=
wyers=E2=80=99 jobs:
The LegalDDoS of 2027 only hastened the LawBots' dominance; the barrage of =
human-filed lawsuits against them forced the notoriously Luddite courts to =
employ legions of LawBots themselves. Whoops.=C2=A0
Slow Ventures=E2=80=99 Sam Lessin made a good counter argument on Twitter:=
=C2=A0
While none of us want to live in a world with 10x the lawsuits, just like n=
one of us want to sit in traffic, I think he=E2=80=99s right. Increase the =
supply of =E2=80=9Clawyers,=E2=80=9D induce more demand for legal work. Inc=
rease the efficiency of lawyers, paradoxically increase the demand for lega=
l resources.=C2=A0
It will be trivially cheap and easy to turn what would have been a handshak=
e agreement into a legal one, just to be safe. It will be trivially cheap t=
o sue people. In about five minutes, I used ChatGPT to learn how to sue my =
neighbor for planting trees on my property and to generate a complaint.
This is just basic, out of the box ChatGPT. It is very careful to remind me=
 that it is not a lawyer. There are a bunch of companies working on buildin=
g legal-specific AIs that will do a much better and more tailored job than =
this. Like Harvey [ https://substack.com/redirect/46125994-55fb-47ba-a23c-b=
6efe48a4851?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ], which has signed deals with top law firms and PWC and was recently v=
alued at $150 million by Sequoia. And yet=E2=80=A6 a simple ChatGPT convers=
ation was really easy, and free.=C2=A0
I probably wouldn=E2=80=99t spend the legal fees to sue my neighbor over pl=
anting trees in my yard, but would I file a complaint for free plus the cos=
t of the filing fee? I bet a lot of people would. Rich people sue each othe=
r over things all the time because the legal fees aren=E2=80=99t prohibitiv=
e to them, particularly in the context of the sizes of the things they=E2=
=80=99re suing over. Now, average people will be able to sue each other mor=
e easily over much lower value issues.=C2=A0
To Sam=E2=80=99s point, this might actually increase the demand for lawyers=
=2E My neighbor, John Doe, might pony u=
p for a lawyer to defend himself. And=20=
this is just a simple, personal case =E2=80=93 when businesses big and smal=
l sue each other over littler and littler things, or write more and more co=
mplex agreements, they may need to employ both AI and more human lawyers to=
 deal with all of it. This is particularly true if you view lawyers, like c=
onsultants, as a kind of CYA expense.=C2=A0
You can apply a similar logic to any number of professions. Certainly, some=
 jobs will be automated away, but I wonder how many professions will actual=
ly grow because of AI.=C2=A0
Divinely Discontent Customers Will Always Want More and Better
Another way of looking at this idea is, confusingly, a different kind of de=
mand curve described by Eugene Wei in Invisible Asymptotes [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/7603f9fc-894b-49e1-950b-b150c0754b83?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ]: =E2=80=9CWe speak often of=20=
the economics concept of the demand curve, but in product there is another =
form of demand curve, and that is the contour of the customers' demands of =
your product or service.=E2=80=9D Wei quotes Jeff Bezos=E2=80=99 2017 lette=
r to shareholders [ https://substack.com/redirect/6f0284a5-5f36-4235-95ea-9=
a709f8253b0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ]:
One thing I love about customers is that they are divinely discontent. Thei=
r expectations are never static =E2=80=93 they go up. It=E2=80=99s human na=
ture.=C2=A0
As supply or capacity increases, customers will simply demand more and bett=
er products. Latent demand grows over time, as consumers see what=E2=80=99s=
 possible today and demand more and better tomorrow.=C2=A0
This is apparent in the world of atoms, where induced demand was born. When=
 we get cheaper energy, we simply demand more and better energy-consuming p=
roducts. When we get more lanes, we simply demand more driving.=C2=A0
I suspect the same will be true for intelligence.=C2=A0
Will AI take lawyers=E2=80=99 jobs, or will we simply sue each other more?=
=C2=A0
Will it take designers=E2=80=99 jobs, or will we demand better design?=C2=
=A0
Will it take doctors=E2=80=99 jobs, or will we all demand our own concierge=
 doctors?=C2=A0
Will it take engineers=E2=80=99 jobs, or will we demand more personalized a=
nd higher-quality software?
Will it replace startups, or will we demand more diverse and better instant=
iations of founders=E2=80=99 visions, faster?
Will it take writers=E2=80=99 jobs, or will readers just demand higher-qual=
ity, more well-researched, more original work?=C2=A0
On the surface, AI looks like an opportunity for humans to do the same work=
 with less effort, and that=E2=80=99s certainly one possibility. The past f=
ew weeks=E2=80=99 rise of AutoGPTs =E2=80=93 agents like Auto-GPT [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/c4729626-455c-4ada-ab8c-46143f1a32cd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and Yohei Nakajima=E2=
=80=99s BabyAGI [ https://substack.com/redirect/045c0a1d-ecd9-42fb-a046-6d8=
18cca3eac?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] that act as semi-autonomous workers =E2=80=93 lend credence to this cam=
p. Maybe we=E2=80=99ll all be the CEO of our own bot armies, directing them=
 with the occasional prompt as we sip pina coladas on the beach. Maybe we=
=E2=80=99ll get a three-day workweek in the near future.=C2=A0
Maybe. But I doubt it.
I suspect that the increased supply of work will induce demand for that ver=
y human skill of figuring out just what we should be working on. It would b=
e a tragic self-own if we used our new superpowers to endlessly sue each ot=
her back and forth.=C2=A0
Will it force us to change how we work? Of course. Will it push us to diffe=
rentiate [ https://substack.com/redirect/cc36cbfe-b463-4e36-934a-ec7e7535b8=
7c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]? Ab=
solutely.
But that could be a wonderful opportunity. Instead of worrying yourself int=
o paralysis, digging your heels in to do more of the same thing, or plannin=
g your next lawsuit, I=E2=80=99d encourage you to take some of your newfoun=
d free time to paint a vision of the future you want to build with superabu=
ndant intelligence, and then get to work.
Thanks to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/211ac028-9ae4-47b4-bd4b-c094e=
e5658eb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] and Puja [ https://substack.com/redirect/e30ce220-295f-4000-8154-897e0f14=
de6e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] f=
or editing!=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 AM with the Weekly Dose.
Thanks for reading,=20
Packy

