ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Induced demand, Jevons Paradox, the =
Marchetti constant, and consumer psychology 101 suggest that </span><strong=
>the increased supply of intelligence will create more demand for tasks tha=
t require intelligence</strong><span>, that we&#8217;ll turn gains in intel=
ligence efficiency into ways of doing new things that weren&#8217;t previou=
sly feasible.&nbsp;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Instead of a zero sum competi=
tion with the bots, we might be on the cusp of </span><strong>intelligence =
superabundance</strong><span>. We may the same amount of time working, we&#=
8217;ll just achieve much more in those hours than we currently do.&nbsp;</=
span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Parkinson&#8217;s Law</strong><span> &#8211; tha=
t the amount of work expands to fill the time available for its completion<=
/span><strong> &#8211; </strong><span>suggests that when each discrete piec=
e of work takes less time, the </span><em>amount</em><span> of work will ex=
pand to fill the rest of the time. But that&#8217;s just a rule of thumb.</=
span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>We can examine it a little more rigorously with a =
little mental flip. Instead of thinking about AI as something separate from=
 human intelligence, we should think of it as an </span><strong>increase in=
 the overall supply of intelligence</strong><span>.&nbsp;</span></p><p styl=
e=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0=
;"><span>As internet pioneer David Gelernter wrote in a prescient 2010 piec=
e, </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/9369c973-49d0-4216-b=
55a-9e2c0abcaf90?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
