eam Logic, The Internet, and Artificial Thought</a></em><span>, &#8220;Huma=
n intelligence is the most valuable stuff in the cosmos, and we are always =
running short. A computer-created increase in the world-wide intelligence s=
upply would be welcome, to say the least.&#8221;&nbsp;There&#8217;s latent =
demand for brainspace.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Treating intelligence as a resou=
rce with a growing supply, we can use economic theories like induced demand=
 and Jevons Paradox, the Marchetti constant, and even observations from Jef=
f Bezos to explore the idea that with AI, humans will need to do more, bett=
er.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Then the important question becomes not &#8220=
;Will I lose my job?&#8221; but </span><strong>&#8220;What would I do with =
superabundant intelligence?&#8221;</strong><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p style=
=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
">We&#8217;ll get there, but first, a little econ.&nbsp;</p><h3 class=3D"he=
