16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;"><strong>Induced Demand =
and Jevons Paradox</strong></h3><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px=
; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Induced demand</strong><s=
pan> is one of the funniest concepts in economics, and I think it&#8217;s o=
ne of the most important to understand in an environment of abundance, be i=
t physical or digital.&nbsp;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Here&#8217;s a simple defi=
nition: induced demand occurs when an increase in the supply or capacity of=
 a good, service, or resource leads to an increase in its consumption. Supp=
ly begets demand.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; lin=
e-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>This isn&#8217;t true of everyth=
ing, of course. 10x&#8217;ing soda production wouldn&#8217;t increase soda =
consumption by 10x. Induced demand mainly holds in cases where there&#8217;=
s </span><em>latent demand</em><span>, where people would use more of a thi=
ng if only more existed, or existed accessibly enough to use.&nbsp;&nbsp;</=
span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 20px 0;">Traffic is the canonical, super frustrating example. The=
 idea is that adding new roads or lanes does practically nothing to reduce =
traffic. More cars just hit the road to fill up the new capacity, and the t=
raffic is right back where it started. The result is that more people are s=
tuck in traffic.</p><div class=3D"captioned-image-container-static" style=
